AGI - The Turkish presidential administration rejected appeals for early presidential elections, after the defeat of President Recep Tayyip Erdogan's party, Akp, yesterday's administration. "The mandate of Erdogan will last until 2028", its natural expiry, wrote on X the presidential chief advisor Mehmet Ucum. According to preliminary data, in yesterday's administrations, for the first time in 20 years the Republican People's Party (Chp), to the opposition, passed the Justice and Development Party (Akp), to power. Experts cited the country's difficult economic situation as a reason for Akp's failure; According to their forecasts, the opposition may require early presidential elections. "To think that there will be an impact of local elections on general elections is nothing but empty imagination," Ucum wrote. "There might be people who have these dreams, but the system rejects such appeals," warned the presidential adviser, "I think that those who make calculations for the general elections according to the votes obtained from the parties in local councils should not waste time." "Turkey will implement reform policies in all sectors during the next four years without elections until 2028. President Erdogan will lead Turkey to new phases with its national leadership, in the perspective of a strong and independent Turkey. No one must have doubts," concluded Ucum.&nbsp;
