AGI - Exemption of ultra-orthodox Jews from military service in Israel ends today, due to a ruling by the Supreme Court, after years of referral. It is a delicate matter that divides Israeli society > against the background of the war between Israel and Palestinian Hamas. Military service is mandatory in Israel, but the ultra-orthodox can avoid conscription if they devote their time to studying the sacred texts of Judaism. The exemption was decided by Ben-Gurion at the creation of the State of Israel in 1948, initially for 400 young people, but today it concerns 66,000 men between 18 and 26 years.
&nbsp;
The law that allowed it was invalidated in 2012 by the Supreme Court that asked for a reform, but the governments and ultra-orthodox parties that succeeded have always concluded interim agreements, without ever being able to find a solution. Over the years, criticisms have increased in Israeli society and secular parties and NGOs have brought the matter to the Supreme Court to seek the immediate conscription of the ultra-orthodox in the name of the principle of equality. The High Court had granted the Government time until 27 March to submit a proposal, but Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu> sent a letter the following day asking for a 30-day extension. On the same day, the Supreme Court issued a provisional judgment which provides, from 1 April, the freezing of public funds for students of Talmudic schools who do not present themselves for military service, but without giving a term for sanctions against those who refuse to provide military service. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
What's going to happen today? These young people could in theory be called to provide military service, explains Yair Ettinger, expert in religious issues of the public broadcaster Kan 11, "but the police will not come to arrest them because it will take some time to declare them deserters, and the Court will have to pronounce on this issue in May. "The ultra-orthodox leaders want a new law to ensure that their students are not forced to enlist in the army, but it will not be easy neither politically nor legally," adds Ettinger.
&nbsp;
The coalition government of Netanyahu is largely based on the alliance with the two main ultra-orthodox parties, Shass and United Torah Judaism, fiercely opposed to the conscription of ultra-orthodox Jews (haredim, Hebrew). Their exit would bring down the coalition. But the option of new elections caused by the ultra-orthodox seems unlikely as "this government is the most favorable to the interests of haredim".
&nbsp;
In May 2023, the government approved an unprecedented budget of nearly a billion euros (3.7 billion shekels) for schools in Talmudic. From today's point of view, the Supreme Court will force the government to cut the budget for these religious institutes. Since the age limit to enlist in the army is 26 years old, it will be deprived of approximately 500 million shekels, the sum allocated for students from 18 to 26 years.
&nbsp;
According to a recent survey, 70% of the Jewish population of the country believes that the ultra-orthodox Jews should, like others, contribute to the country's security and serve military service, while the war launched by Israel in Gaza after the unpublished October attack perpetrated by Hamas will enter its sixth month. Almost 600 Israeli soldiers have fallen since the beginning of the war in Gaza, 254 of them in the Strip, with over 3,000 wounded.

